{{Infobox Protected area | name = Rago National Park | iucn_category = II | photo = Rago National Park logo.svg | photo_width = 180 | photo_caption = | map_image = Rago001.jpg | location = [[Sørfold]], [[Nordland]], [[Norway]] | nearest_city = [[Fauske]] | coords = {{coord|67|26|N|15|59|E|region:NO|display=inline,title}} | area_km2 = 171 | established = 1971 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = [[Norwegian Directorate for Nature Management|Directorate for Nature Management]] }}
'''Rago National Park''' ({{lang-no|Rago nasjonalpark}}) is a [[national park]] in the municipality of [[Sørfold]] in [[Nordland]] county, [[Norway]]. The {{convert|171|km2|adj=on}} park lies east of [[European route E06]], about {{convert|10|km}} northeast of the village of [[Straumen, Nordland|Straumen]]. The park was established on 22 January 1971.<ref name="snl">{{cite web|url=http://snl.no/Rago_nasjonalpark|title=Rago nasjonalpark|author=Store norske leksikon|authorlink=Store norske leksikon|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2012-04-05}}</ref> [[File:Rago national park.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Valley in Rago NP]]
Rago borders [[Sweden]]'s [[Padjelanta National Park]], which in turn borders two other parks, and the combined of all the protected land is a total of ca. {{convert|5400|km2}}&mdash;creating one of the largest protected areas in [[Europe]].
The lakes [[Storskogvatnet]] and [[Litlverivatnet]] lie within the park. There are several [[glacier]]s in the southeastern part of the park. Rago National Park does not have a rich variety of plants, due partly to its poor soils and harsh climate. The wooded areas consist mostly of pine. Many alpine plants grow among the trees.<ref name="DN">{{cite web|url=http://english.dirnat.no/content/500044119/Rago-national-park-brochure|title=Rago national park|publisher=[[Norwegian Directorate for Nature Management]]|accessdate=2012-04-05|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407235243/http://english.dirnat.no/content/500044119/Rago-national-park-brochure|archivedate=2012-04-07|df=}}</ref>
There isn't a wide variety of animal and bird life either. [[Moose]] live in the park along with semi-domesticated [[reindeer]]. There are also [[wolverine]]s in the park. [[Willow grouse]] and [[golden eagle]]s are frequently seen in the park.<ref name="DN" />
==Name== The name is a shortened form of the [[Sami languages|Sami]] name ''Rágojiegna''. The first element is the genitive case of ''ráhko'' which means "sledge for tent poles" and the last element is ''jiegna'' which means "[[glacier]]".
